ent of Statistics Canada, the National Productivity Council, and the evolution of the Atlantic Canada Opportunities Agency, Foster argues that there is a ‘productivist regime’ guiding policy development in Canada and abroad. By analyzing and critiquing the inherent assumptions of productivism the author destabilizes the myth that economic growth is essential for quality of life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aIndustrial productivityxCase studiesxCanada. 0aIndustrial productivityxCase studiesxGovernment policyxCanada. 0aIndustrial productivityxGovernment policyzCanadavCase studies. 0aIndustrial productivityzCanadavCase studies. 0aProductivitéxÉtudes de casxCanada. 0aProductivitéxÉtudes de casxPolitique gouvernementalexCanada. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066595640uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148751181440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487511814423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487511814.jpg  a978-3-11-066595-6  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles